Affordable House Price Estimator UI Implementation

For this project, the UI implementation was developed using Streamlit to create a simple and interactive interface for the Affordable Housing Price Estimator. The purpose of the UI was to allow users to enter property details and instantly view the predicted house price without interacting directly with the backend code. The dataset used for this project is Bengaluru_House_Data_Cleaned.csv, which contains cleaned housing data including features such as total square footage, number of bathrooms, number of balconies, and distance to the nearest metro station. These same features were used in the UI as input fields.
In the Streamlit interface, users can enter values for total square feet, number of bathrooms, number of balconies, and distance to metro (in meters). Once the inputs are provided, the application converts them into a structured format and passes them to the pre-trained machine learning model for prediction. The model then returns the estimated house price in Lakhs as well as in Rupees, and based on a defined threshold, the system displays whether the property is considered affordable or expensive. The UI was designed to be minimal, clear, and user-friendly so that anyone can easily test different property values and understand how the prediction changes.
streamlit for building the UI, pickle for loading the trained machine learning model, and numpy for handling numerical data. After importing, the trained house price prediction model is loaded from the file house_price_model.pkl using pickle.load(). This connects the frontend interface with the already trained backend model.
Next, a variable called avg_price is defined, which is used as a reference value to decide whether a house is affordable or expensive. Then, the title of the application is displayed using st.title(), and a short instruction is shown using st.write() to guide the user to enter house details.
For taking input from the user, st.number_input() is used multiple times. This creates input fields where the user can enter values such as square footage, number of bathrooms, number of balconies, and distance to the metro station. The min_value parameter ensures that users cannot enter unrealistic values (for example, square footage cannot be less than 1000). These inputs are stored in variables like sqft, bath, balcony, and distance.
When the user clicks the “Predict Price” button using st.button(), the program collects all the entered values and stores them in a structured format (usually as a NumPy array) so that it matches the format expected by the trained model. Then, the model.predict() function is called. This function takes the input data and returns the predicted house price. Since the model returns the result in an array format, [0] is used to extract the actual predicted value.
After getting the prediction, the result is displayed using st.subheader() and st.write(). The predicted price is shown both in Lakhs and in Rupees. The conversion to Rupees is done by multiplying the predicted value by 100000, since 1 lakh equals 100,000 rupees.
Finally, a simple condition checks whether the predicted price is less than the predefined average price (avg_price). If it is less, the house is marked as “Affordable” using st.success(), which shows a green message. Otherwise, it displays “Expensive” using st.error(), which shows a red message.
The goal was to make the application easy to use, even for someone without technical knowledge. By integrating the saved model and scaler files directly into the UI script, the application avoids retraining the model each time and produces quick predictions. This implementation demonstrates how a machine learning model can be practically deployed with a basic yet effective user interface.

NOTE : During the UI implementation, a minor naming mistake occurred where the title was written as “Affordable House Price Predictor” instead of “Affordable Housing Price Estimator.” Both refer to the same project, and the correct intended title is “Affordable Housing Price Estimator.” This clarification is provided to avoid confusion when reviewing the output.
